[[File:冨士山下宮小室浅間神社_JRA奉納_神馬_瑞桜（ヒカリシャーク）.jpg|alt=奉納された神馬。競走馬を引退したサラブレッドが、神馬として奉納されている（山梨県富士吉田市　冨士山下宮小室浅間神社）|thumb]]
'''Shinme''' (神馬, also read as Jinme or Kami-uma) refers to sacred horses revered as mounts for the gods in Japanese Shinto shrines. These horses, typically white, are dedicated to shrines or appear during festivals.
[[Image:Shinme(Geku) 01.JPG|thumb|240px|alt=Shinme(Geku)_01.JPG|Sacred stable at {{ill|Toyouke Daijingu|ja|豊受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Outer Shrine of {{ill|Ise Jingu|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). Shinme named "Okaaki."]]

== Overview ==
[[File:Shinme - KagawaKen-Gokoku-jinja.jpg|thumb|200px|Metal statue of a Shinme ({{ill|Kagawa Prefecture Gokoku Shrine|ja|香川縣護國神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}})]]
[[File:Hotaka-jinja14bs5s2040.jpg|thumb|200px|Wooden statue of a Shinme ({{ill|Hotaka Shrine|ja|穂高神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}})]]
Since the Nara period, it has been customary to dedicate horses to shrines as prayers. Donors range from commoners to imperial family members.

Due to the high cost and maintenance burden, many shrines replaced real horses with '''{{ill|Ema|ja|絵馬|1=Ema (Shinto)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (horse paintings)<ref>For instance, historical texts such as the "Shoku Nihongi" and "Engishiki" mention dedicating black horses for rain, later replaced by Ema in the Noh play {{ill|Ema (Noh)|ja|絵馬 (能)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.</ref>. Life-sized horse statues also commonly serve as Shinme.

The "Engishiki" (Vol. 3, Clause 26) states black horses were dedicated for rain prayers<ref>Example: "Shoku Nihongi," Hōki 3 (772), February 24th, describes dedicating a black horse to {{ill|Niukawakami Shrine|ja|丹生川上神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Yamato Province during droughts.</ref>, and white horses for clear weather. This tradition is echoed in the Noh play {{ill|Ema (Noh)|ja|絵馬 (能)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref>Gondō Yoshikazu, "Nōgaku Techō," Shinjindō, 1979, pp.58-59.</ref>. Medieval warriors also dedicated horses for victory prayers.

Shrines often maintain "Shinme-sha" or "Shinkyu-sha" (sacred stables), even without actual horses, reflecting this tradition. Retired thoroughbred racehorses are sometimes dedicated as Shinme.

According to the Chinese text "Furui Zu," a blue-black horse with white mane and tail was considered auspicious. The "Shoku Nihongi" also records a sacred horse from Higo Province presented in 768.

